description: An excellent blend of salmon, pesto, spinach, and puff pastry.  It tastes great and only takes a few minutes to put it all together!

description: Quinoa makes a delightful grain salad when mixed with corn, black beans, tomato, fresh cilantro, and feta cheese.

description: The pan juices from this slow roasted cajun pork loin create an incredible sauce for drizzling over the meat.

description: This is just like you would get at a Cantonese Chinese restaurant. Ground pork, shrimp, and egg are stir-fried in a fragrant sauce.

description: Spam Musubi is a very popular Hawaiian snack that is just like sushi. Marinated sliced luncheon meat is quickly pan seared then placed on top of rice and wrapped in nori (dried seaweed.) Try it, you'll like it!

description: Chicken that is both savory and sweet, with dried onion soup and pineapple and fresh oranges.

description: If you need a quick snack for a busy morning, these make-ahead sticky buns are perfect.

description: Raw peanuts in their shells simmer in a salty, spicy brew flavored with crab boil, Cajun seasoning, garlic, and two kinds of serious hot peppers. This is the real deal that is found in the heart of Florida.

If added while the gumbo is still cooking, it may become stringy and unpleasant.  File is ground sassafras leaves.  It is available in many supermarkets.

description: Pears and crystallized ginger are baked under a crispy golden oat crust.

description: Green beans in a bright, tangy dressing that combines balsamic vinegar, olive oil, shallots, and garlic. Served cold.

description: Fresh avocados combine with bacon, green onions, sour cream, and a splash of lemon. Spooned over red leaf lettuce, it's a refreshing salad.

description: A creamy casserole made with chops and tots! Sure to be a family favorite.

description: Instead of cooking your corned beef on the stovetop, try it in the oven! Plan on 1 hour of roasting time per pound of beef.

description: This was my mother's finest fish meal growing up. Even people we know who aren't fish fanatics love this dish. It can be served with rice but we love it with linguine.

Once you master the technique, you can make them very quickly and will find the texture and appearance to be much better than rolled biscuits.

description: An indulgence of fries, gravy and cheese. A Canadian specialty!

description: Eat while clutching cold brewski in other hand. Yah, hey dere.

description: A spicy breading gives a crunch to these oven-fried catfish fillets.

description: A tasty and clean way to bake salmon! Serve in paper with buttered new potatoes. Yummy!

description: A fun way to make a family favorite. It tastes a little different than the commercial stuff, but it is much better. Above all things, have fun and feel free to experiment! Try adding fruit extract, if you like.

description: A quick and tasty chicken dish, cooked first on the stove with onions and mushrooms, then popped into the oven for a few minutes to melt cheese on top.

description: There couldn't be a better way to prepare freshly caught wild brook trout. Serve with a side of creamy mashed potatoes and steamed Swiss chard.

description: These stay fresh a long time, but with chocolate chips, oatmeal, coconut, and cornflakes, these yummy cookies won't last long. So grab 'em while you can!

description: Great catfish baked with a cornmeal crust and sprinkled with crushed pecans.

description: New York Strip on a grill has never been easier. This recipe is easy and ingredients are usually around the house!

description: A bar-room staple, these fiery little chicken wings are basted in a hot-pepper sauce, then cooled with tangy blue cheese dip.

description: I've always called this a buckle (I'm from the Midwest), but my friends here in California, say it's a 'coffee cake', but no matter the name they love it!

description: This is my mom's favorite salad. My grandmother always made it during the holidays in Alabama.

description: Tender red beans, sliced hickory-smoked pork sausage, onion, celery, and bell pepper are spiced with Cajun seasoning in this comforting meal. Best served over hot cooked rice.

description: Great for brushing over chicken or pork during the final grilling or smoking phase, this Alabama-style white barbeque sauce is a surefire hit.

description: Baked salmon fillets with a crunchy pecan coating make an excellent main course.

description: A wonderfully simple recipe for baked salmon. The flavors of lemon and dill really complement the fish.

I have had to come up with some pretty creative ways to prepare salmon, this is by far my family and friends favorite way to eat fresh salmon.  I soak an untreated cedar plank in water and bourbon while they are out fishing for the day and fix the barbeque sauce so that's it is ready to get grilling.....

The owners are very good friends of mine, and the culinary creations at this fishing lodge are out of this world!  I promise, one of these cookies will fill you as much as a cheeseburger and fries would!

description: Stew meat slow cooked with bacon and onion in a savory sauce of brown sugar, vinegar, mustard, ketchup and spices.

description: This meal is very yummy, juicy, easy to cook, and convenient. It's ready in half an hour!

description: Salmon fillets are topped with red wine vinegar, orange segments, and green onions for an easy, elegant dish that's ready in 30 minutes.

description: Spicy, creamy, and colorful, this recipe is a splendid update to the Mexican spinach dip.

description: This is an easy and delicious way to use either fresh or frozen salmon. Being from Alaska, our family puts up with a lot of salmon during the summer. This is a very good recipe to use in the middle of winter when your family is saying no more fish please!

description: Just like a Texas Sheet Cake, it uses the technique of boiling the water and butter, and it has a pecan frosting - but it's white instead of chocolate.

description: You'll get rave reviews on this macadamia-cilantro pesto, it's just wonderful with crispy seared salmon and scallops!

description: It only takes 15 minutes to prepare the meat for the slow cooker. After 10 hours, the flavorful, tender meat is ready to be shredded and served to a crowd!

description: Salmon burgers held together with almond meal and eggs are a quick and easy, paleo-friendly snack or dinner item.

description: Hearty caribou stew with plenty of vegetables and seasonings cooks all day in the slow cooker for a warm and comforting meal on cold evenings.

description: This traditional Dutch cookie recipe came with a mold I got 20 years ago. Speculaas is a corruption of the Latin speculum (mirror). The dough is pressed into carved molds that can be used for wall decorations.  When turned out onto the cookie sheet, the picture appears as its mirror image, hence the name.  In the Sinterklass season they are available in 2/3 cookie size to huge thick men and women up to 1 pound known as lovers. If molds are not available, roll dough to desired thickness and use gingerbread man cutter or other cutter shapes. They are great to make ahead around Christmas because they last a long time.
title: Speculaas Cookies or Spicy Sinterklass Cakes

description: An old recipe that's especially good for family get-togethers. It's good, it's fun, and clean-up is easy. It's best done outside around a picnic table. When shrimp and crabs are done, cover picnic table with four to five layers of newspaper. Remove everything from pot, drain, and spread in center of table. Gather everyone around and enjoy the feast. When everyone has had their fill, gather up the leftovers (if there is any), put all the scraps in the center of the table, roll up the newspaper around them, and put them in the trash. Go wash the one pot and the cleanup is done. Have fun and enjoy.

description: This dish is a bonanza of baked beans! Chili sauce adds a little spiciness. Don't be dissuaded by the lima beans - they blend into the mix wonderfully!

description: This recipe has been in my family for many, many years.  My late mother heard this recipe given out on the radio one day years and years ago and she made them.  They are delicious and I am forwarding the recipe to you because I am afraid it may otherwise become lost over time and I wish to share it with you.

title: Buckeye Cookies II

description: This is a comforting baked stew with a rich cheese sauce. Children and adults will both agree that this is delicious.
title: Ohio Meat Pie

description: The traditional chocolate-covered peanut butter buckeye gets a crunchy twist with the addition of crispy rice cereal to the mix.
title: Krispy Buckeyes

description: The traditional ingredients of chocolate and peanut butter are layered in a jelly roll pan creating easy-to-eat buckeye bars.
title: Easy Buckeye Bars

description: This slightly-different baked pasta casserole is a definite kid pleaser.
title: Best Bresslin' Pasta Casserole Done Cincinnati Style

description: A vintage sweet tomato pudding reminds us that tomatoes are a fruit. Start your own Thanksgiving tradition with this savory-sweet midwestern dish.
title: Ohio Tomato Pudding

description: Like a nicely flecked tweed suit, miniature chocolate chips speckle a vanilla cake base, topped with vanilla frosting and dark chocolate.
title: Tweed Squares

description: A classically easy chili recipe with four additional variations ranging from Cincinnati to Morocco.
title: Beef Chili Five Ways

description: This recipe for Thai carrot salad with peanuts is a perfect balance of sweet and spicy with hints of garlic and curry in the dressing.
title: Thai Carrot Salad

description: Love the cinnamon, cocoa, and chili flavors of classic Cincinnati Chili? This version of Cincinnati-style chili is ready in only 30 minutes!
title: Cincinnati-Style Chili & Rice

description: A variation on the classic chicken and dumpling casserole, this flavorful main dish shows its Hungarian roots with colorful paprika used to season a sour cream sauce.
title: Chicken Paprikash

description: Cabbage and noodles, cooked with bacon, is comfort food supreme, great for a chilly day.
title: Cabbage and Noodles

description: Chicken pieces stewed in a sauce mixture including the traditional Hungarian ingredient - paprika - along with other spices and sour cream. This is our family recipe for Chicken Paprikash. Very good on cold days, and good served over dumplings.
title: Chicken Paprikash II

description: A buttery saute of shredded cabbage and chopped onion is folded into tender egg noodles to make a quick and comforting dish.
title: Polish Cabbage Noodles

description: Delectable pork cubes, coated, skewered and slow simmered in chicken broth and herbs.  Serve over rice, noodles, or mashed potatoes.
title: City Chicken

description: Orangey-red paprika imparts a slightly sweet, slightly hot flavor and a lot of color to this sour cream sauce.
title: Chicken Paprikash I

description: Shredded chicken meat is heated up with condensed cream of mushroom soup and crushed butter crackers, and served hot on a bun.
title: Hot Shredded Chicken Sandwiches

description: Brown and white sugars, raisins and lemon juice add a wonderful taste and texture to this quintessential apple pie. Be sure to cube or slice the apples uniformly, and, if you like, dot the apples with pats of butter.
title: American Apple Pie

description: These rye slices topped with sausage and cheese are so easy and so delicious that they are sure to please. In fact, my husband loves them so much that I sometimes make them on regular-sized rye bread for dinner.
title: Hanky Pankies

description: This is a recipe I found in my grandfathers recipe box. I made it the first time simply because I happened to have all the needed ingredients.  Now I make it because it tastes so yummy!
title: Lemon Chiffon Pudding

description: Deep fried and savory, these delicious little sausage sauerkraut balls are the perfect party finger food.  These are the most scrumptious sauerkraut balls you will ever taste!!
title: Scrumptious Sauerkraut Balls

description: Cassata cake is like a cannoli but more gooey. You need 2 - 9 inch sponge cake layers for this recipe. The instructions are given for to make them, or you can use your own recipe.
title: Cassata Cake

description: A hearty combination of steak and veggies make the filling for these delicious individual pastries. The pastry rolls out beautifully, and bakes up golden brown. These are perfect for lunchboxes or a casual supper.
title: Cornish Pasty

description: This recipe makes about 75 tangy and delicious fried sauerkraut balls.
title: Sauerkraut Balls

description: This pie is pure elderberry with sugar, a hint of lemon juice, and cornstarch stirred in. The top crust is latticed so when you take it from the oven, you can see the beautiful berries and bubbly sauce glisten through it.
title: Elderberry Pie II

description: An unusual baking ingredient--sauerkraut--lends a satisfying crunch to these savory doughnuts.
title: Sauerkraut Balls

description: A mixture of hamburger, mild sausage and Worcestershire sauce with processed cheese melted on top. Makes a delicious snack or quick meal. Serve it on toasted slices of your favorite bread.
title: Hanky Panky

description: Rye bread filled with corned beef, sauerkraut and mozzarella and fried in a skillet until hot and gooey.
title: Reuben Sandwich I

description: This is a delightful appetizer that can be made ahead of time and heated when guests arrive. Spicy pork sausage and beef will never know what hit them when you blend them with sauerkraut and a cream cheese mixture, then deep fry them to mouthwatering golden perfection.
title: Sauerkraut Sausage Balls

description: Here's a hearty and comforting meal with garbanzo beans, sweet Italian sausage, and pasta in a tomato-based sauce.
title: Garbanzo Bean and Sausage Stew

description: A flavorful sausage and sauerkraut mixture is breaded and baked into delicious appetizer balls.
title: Sausage Sauerkraut Balls

description: Puff pastry cookies wrapped on clothes pins, baked and then filled.  1/2 inch to 5/8 inch dowels cut 4 inches long work well.  Clothes pins may spring open in the oven and break the pastry.  These are best if baked on insulated cookie sheets.
title: Clothes Pin Cookies

description: This is a much easier version of clothes pin cookies.
title: Clothespin Cookies II

description: This recipe for delicious walnut filling is meant to be the filling for kolacky cookies.
title: Nut Filling for Kolacky Cookies

description: Gooey, cream cheese and lemon center. Crispy, nutty top.  Bar cookies made with two kinds of cake mix.
title: Old Lady Cleveland's Gooey Bars

description: Swiss chard, seasonal fresh herbs, and fresh mozzarella cheese make up a fresh baked quiche stuffing for a big zucchini from your garden. There's a browned crumb topping, too.
title: Swiss Chard and Mozzarella Quiche in Zucchini Crust

description: The berries in this wonderful double-crust pie are doused with lemon juice for a little zip. Sugar, flour and salt are sprinkled over the glistening berries, and the top crust is sealed and fluted. It 's then plopped into a hot oven and baked until the crust is golden.
title: Elderberry Pie III

description: Keep an eye out for a farm stand offering elderberries and rush back home to make this amazing double-crust pie. The fresh berries are combined with seedless grapes, brown sugar, a bit of flour and cinnamon, and then the mixture is doused with vinegar before the whole thing is baked in a hot oven for 45 minutes.
title: Elderberry Pie I

description: This is a recipe my Bohemian grandmother used to make for Easter every year.  I was fortunate enough to have learned how to make it before she passed away and my family says I nailed her recipe on the head.  The key: lots of garlic and chives and onions!  Sorry the quantity is so large, but I have no idea how to scale it down much more.  My grandma said 'back in the day' there were a lot of Bohemians in the neighborhood and they would use crates of eggs and make the mixture in the bathtub!
title: Sekanice (Easter Meatloaf)

description: A homemade crust made with butter and egg yolk encases this classic Southern style pecan pie.
title: Southern Pecan Pie II

description: This bean chowder is similar to chili. It's one of the most popular dishes at Tulsa Public Schools. Those of us growing up in the 60's and 70's remember it fondly as a favorite treat. A real stick-to-your-ribs comfort food. Tradition dictates that it is served with cinnamon rolls. This was given to me by my grandmother who was a dietician/cook for over 40 years.
title: Brown Bean Chowder

description: These Tater Wedges are a great side dish when grilling. A great mixture of seasonings give them the pep they need to tickle your taste buds. Add more cayenne pepper if you really like it spicy.
title: Spiced-Up Grilled Tater Wedges

description: This hearty pinto bean dish uses smoked ham hock to add flavor and richness. A bit of tomato sauce and brown sugar gives this meal a little zing.
title: Best Ever Pinto Beans

description: Quick and easy with few ingredients. Great for an on-the-fly marinade. Tangy Italian dressing and Worcestershire are used to accentuate the natural flavor of the cut, while the minced garlic provides a delectable rich flavor.
title: Tangy Garlic Steak

description: Oklahoma style spicy beer and tomato-vegetable juice drink.
title: JoeDogg's Spicy Red Beer

description: Easy-to-make fry bread needs just two ingredients, self-rising flour and buttermilk. Top the golden brown fried breads with a spicy ground beef and bean mixture, then garnish with your favorite taco trimmings.
title: Oklahoma Indian Tacos

description: Kolaches are a Czech recipe that are traditionally made with a yeast dough and fruit filling.  In this version a non-yeasted dough is used.
title: Apricot Kolaches

description: Tender, juicy roast beef - cooked outdoors on the rotisserie!
title: Slow Roasted BBQ Beef Roast

description: Catfish fillets are coated with a steak seasoning and cornmeal mixture, and fried to golden perfection.
title: Choctaw Catfish

description: For sensational flavor, rub nice thick tenderloin steaks with olive oil, crushed garlic and meat tenderizer. Let the meat sit for a bit and then grill.
title: Easy Barbeque Beef Tenderloin Steak

description: The unusual combination of ingredients--green beans, cabbage, onions, and bratwurst--in this stove-top casserole is one Oklahoma family's traditional comfort food. The dish also freezes and reheats well.
title: Oklahoma Comfort Food: Brats, Cabbage and Green Bean Casserole

description: My Mom, sisters and I would not feel like it was Christmas unless we had made this delicious candy.  It tastes somewhere between fudge and caramels. It's best to use a wooden spoon to stir this candy with.
title: Oklahoma Nut Candy

description: This is a rich loaf with sour cream and canned corn for extra flavor.  Try adding chopped peppers or onions for variations on the theme.
title: Corn Cornbread

description: Canned beef tamales and cooked chicken are combined in this easy, hearty, Southwestern themed casserole.
title: Oklahoma Tamale Casserole

description: Soft cheese tacos include corn tortillas rolled around Cheddar cheese that are topped with a cheese sauce for a Mexican-inspired comfort food.
title: Soft Cheese Tacos

description: Buttermilk makes this devil's food cake moist and tender, perfect for bakers at high altitudes looking to make a celebratory 3-layer cake.
title: High-Altitude Buttermilk Devil's Food Cake

description: An easy and yummy blackberry pie that is thickened with tapioca.
title: Blackberry Pie IV

description: Spicy and tasty come to mind. Ginger, garlic and crushed red chilies are cooked in a bit of oil and then green beans are tossed in. That cooks for a few minutes and then soy and oyster sauce are added. When the sauce thickens, it 's time to serve.
title: Oriental Green Bean Salad

description: Fresh summer raspberries in raspberry jam on a buttery crust.
title: Raspberry Tart

description: Make a homemade version of a chai tea latte with boiling water, milk, sugar, honey, and a tea bag.
title: Chai Tea Latte

description: Spicy cookies are a beloved Christmas treat in Denmark and throughout Scandinavia where expensive spices were traditionally reserved for special holiday foods. These tiny (nut-free) butter cookies burst with flavor from cardamom, cinnamon, nutmeg, and cloves.
title: Danish Peppernut Christmas Cookies (Pebernodder)

description: A cold shrimp and crab salad with pasta, celery, onion, and green pepper. Imitation crabmeat also works well in place of real crab. Can also be made with salmon or tuna in place of shrimp and crab.
title: Shrimp and Crab Macaroni Salad

description: I obtained this recipe 40-years ago from the cook at the Highway Cafe in Scappoose, Oregon.  I have never found its equal. Whenever I serve it, I am always asked for the recipe.
title: Highway Cafe Chess Pie

description: This deliciously dense chocolate cake is sure to satisfy even the biggest chocoholic!
title: Chocolate Chocolate Cake

description: A sweet and spicy fresh fruit salsa starring kiwi, strawberries, blackberries, and apples; seasoned with cayenne, hot sauce, green salsa, and lime juice. Serve with tortilla chips
title: Spicy Fruit Salsa

description: A quick and elegant strawberry dessert made with fresh strawberries and an irresistible cream sauce. It looks as good as it tastes!
title: Strawberries Romanov

description: Twice-baked cookie that can have miniature chocolate chips in the batter. Use brandy in place of the hazelnut liqueur if you like!
title: Hazelnut Biscotti

description: Fresh ginger and garlic are cooked in vermouth until tender. Soy sauce, oyster sauce, and honey are stirred in and cooked until the flavors have mingled and the sauce thickens. Perfect marinade for vegetables, tofu, chicken, and salmon.
title: Teriyaki Marinade I

description: The citrus marinade used in this recipe is made with sprigs of fresh marjoram.  One or two hours of marinating is all that is required: a longer period affects the texture of the fish.
title: Grilled Halibut I

description: This take on a classic recipe combination of chicken and Marsala wine uses chanterelle mushrooms and plenty of butter to deliver a tasty chicken main dish.
title: Chicken with Chanterelle Mushrooms and Marsala Wine

description: This is a bread machine recipe developed by my very talented mother, who grew up in Oregon, the Filbert (or Hazelnut) capital of the world! This bread has won raves from those who don't even like whole wheat bread.
title: Mom's Hazelnut Special

description: This recipe is a perfect refresher for a hot summer day or to quench a raging thirst!  Absolutely delicious! To make it thick, simply use berries frozen!
title: Berry Refresher

description: Thin and crispy cookies folded into a triangle shape or a hollow roll. Use brandy in place of the hazelnut liqueur if you like!
title: Hazelnut Lace

description: Warm yourself up with this 'Rainy Portland' drink made with warmed milk, brown sugar, rum, and a hint of butter.
title: Rainy Portland (Warm Rum Drink)

description: Hazelnuts, apples, and sharp Cheddar combine with mixed salad greens and an apple cider vinaigrette to make a hearty Oregon fall salad.
title: Oregon Fall Salad

description: Sweet roasted strawberries are stirred into a creamy coconut base in this soft serve ice cream recipe from Wiz Bang Bar in Portland, Oregon.
title: Wiz Bang Bar's Roasted Strawberry Coconut Soft Serve

description: Peach cobbler can be made with just five simple ingredients that you probably already have on hand. It is a perfect dessert on a hot summer night!
title: Elnora's Peach Cobbler

description: The gob cake is a Pennsylvanian relative of whoopie pie, combining a chocolate cake with sweet, creamy icing, as done in this recipe.
title: Gob Cake

description: With ground beef, plenty of corn, and potatoes, this easy soup is thick and hearty enough to be a meal on its own.
title: Hamburger Corn Soup

description: Refrigerator biscuits help you make short work of getting this yummy treat on the table.  Cinnamon sugar, chopped pecans and margarine coat each morsel of dough, and a drizzling of dark corn syrup makes sure they will be very sticky.
title: Quick Sticky Buns

description: Rivals (a crumb-sized egg noodle) and hard boiled eggs complete this Pennsylvania Dutch recipe for chicken soup with celery and corn fresh off the cob.
title: Chicken Corn Soup I

description: Yummy! Everyone's favorite - gooey, sticky, and rich.
title: Pecan Sticky Buns

description: Pressed ham is simmered in a sauce made with ketchup, vinegar, mustard, and brown sugar to make these Pittsburgh favorites.
title: Pittsburgh Ham Barbecues

description: A mixture of pineapple, flour, butter eggs and cinnamon. Excellent side dish with ham or pork roast. My in-laws are from Pennsylvania; this recipe is from some of the aunts who live there. A Christmas dinner must-have!
title: Pineapple Bake

description: A bubbling, cheesy ham and noodle skillet casserole is the perfect dish for a cozy family supper.
title: Campbell's(R) Pennsylvania Dutch Ham and Noodle Casserole

description: Despite its name, Greek Sauce is actually a regional favorite of western Pennsylvania as a topping for hot dogs, hamburgers, and even French fries. In this iteration of the sauce, ground beef is simmered with a variety of spices, tomato sauce, and mustard.
title: Pennsylvania Greek Sauce

description: Originally of Pennsylvania Dutch origin, scrapple was made from the bits and pieces of the pig not suited for anything else! This streamlined recipe takes only minutes to prepare ... perfect for making the night before.  Serve topped with choice of warmed syrup.
title: Scrapple

description: An easy chicken and pasta casserole is inspired by the famous Philly sandwich, with chicken breasts, green peppers, onions, and Swiss cheese all mixed with rotini pasta and baked.
title: Chicken Philly Pasta

description: This traditional Pennsylvania Dutch treat is flavored with pumpkin puree and pumpkin pie spice, cooked in deep fat until crisp and golden, then dusted with confectioners' sugar.
title: Pumpkin Funnel Cakes

description: This is a recipe that we used in Pennsylvania for kids birthday parties. I remember my parents grinding the bologna in a old fashion meat grinder. They spread it on white bread and cut the sandwiches into triangles. Of course, we also had cake and ice cream.
title: Sandwich Spread

description: A big recipe for Pennsylvania Dutch potato and bread dressing will feed a big table full of people during the holidays.
title: Pennsylvania Dutch Potato Filling

description: A classic Pennsylvania Dutch pie made with molasses, brown sugar and butter.
title: Shoofly Pie V

description: Sweet buttermilk yeast dough cannot quite contain the luscious, buttery cinnamon-sugar filling of these yummy rolls.  They bake on a bed of pecans, butter and brown sugar for the ultimate in sticky sweetness.
title: Sticky Buns I

description: The "wet-bottom" in this pie consists of molasses, corn syrup and water. Brown sugar crumb rest between layers of the molasses mixture.
title: Wet-Bottom Shoofly Pie

description: The sandwiches of this historic Pittsburgh restaurant are legendary. In fact, they're almost famous. Italian bread, fries, pastrami, melted provolone, and homemade coleslaw should quench that craving if you find yourself too far from Pittsburgh.
title: Pittsburgh Sandwich

description: Super-simple and super-fast describes this 4-ingredient chipped ham barbecue recipe. Just combine, heat, and serve for the easiest, quickest Pittsburgh-style chipped ham sandwiches ever.
title: Pittsburgh Style Chipped Ham Barbeque

description: These are Pennsylvania Dutch Funny Cakes, baked in a pie crust with a chocolate "funny" layer that sinks to the bottom while baking.
title: Pennsylvania Dutch Funny Cakes

description: This is a Pennsylvania-Dutch recipe for homemade rice-shaped egg noodles cooked in broth.
title: Rivel Soup

description: Claiming to be the best pork barbeque recipe in the land, this version comes from Harrisburg, Pennsylvania. Dressed up with hot pepper sauce and smoke flavor, this slow cooker pulled pork is an easy solution for crowd pleasing, pork eating fun!
title: Pork Barbeque

description: This hog maw is stuffed with pork sausage, potatoes and cabbage. Grew up with it and I'm still alive and I love this meal.  Good Pennsylvania dish.
title: Hog Maw

description: Pork loin, apples, and sauerkraut are baked together with caraway seeds and brown sugar creating a warm and comforting meal to serve with mashed potatoes and applesauce.
title: Pork Loin, Apples, and Sauerkraut

description: An old fashioned ham loaf recipe that makes 2 loaves with a tangy-sweet sauce is a great way to use up leftovers from a big smoked ham. It's a regional favorite from western Pennsylvania.
title: Gram's Ham Loaf

description: Being an enthusiastic Philadelphia Eagles football fan, I wanted to create a burger recipe that had a taste of Philly, and some green ingredients, as a tribute to the Birds. Play around with the ingredients and create a burger for your favorite team!
title: Eagles Tailgating Burgers

description: This version of the classic pie has delightful hints of nutmeg, ginger, cinnamon, and cloves.
title: Shoofly Pie II

description: Serve this slow cooker pork and sauerkraut with apples on New Year's day for a year of good luck.
title: Slow Cooker Pork and Sauerkraut with Apples

description: Sweet chopped ham, simmered in a slow cooker with chili sauce and cola, makes a great easy sandwich. It's a Pittsburgh thing.
title: Pittsburgh Ham Barbecue Sandwich

description: This Italian riff on the classic Philly Cheesesteak is a meal on a bun. Tender tri-tip steak is pan fried with onion, bell peppers, and hot peppers, then topped with blue cheese and aged provolone.
title: Sicilian Steak Sandwich

description: A variation on the old Pennsylvania Dutch favorite, Shoo Fly Pie. Not as sweet or gooey as Shoo Fly Pie, this cake is much better the day after you bake it. Works really well as cupcakes.  I made mini cupcakes for Christmas, always a hit.
title: Shoo Fly Cake

description: One head fresh cabbage simmered with sour cream, sugar, vinegar, flour, salt, pepper and oil.
title: Pennsylvania Dutch Sour Cream Cabbage

description: Man-sized chunks of vegetables are cooked in a heap of butter, then combined with potatoes, beef and broth for a mountainous stew.
title: Mountain Man Stew

description: Hard-cook egg yolks go in the dressing, while the egg whites are mixed with macaroni, onion, carrot, and celery in this macaroni salad.
title: Amish Picnic Macaroni Salad

description: For this sweet, gooey, luscious pie, chocolate chips are poured into a pastry-lined pie pan. Then a buttery, molasses and brown sugar filling is spooned onto that, and covered with another layer of chocolate chips and a sugar crumble mix. It bakes in less than an hour.
title: Chocolate Shoofly Pie

description: Blueberries take the cake in this favorite family recipe with German/Pennsylvania origins. Spread the shortcake dough over a baking sheet, make a well and spoon blueberry pie filling into each square, then bake for a dessert or breakfast treat.
title: Blubaugh's Blueberry Buckle Shortcake

description: This pasta salad recipe features tomatoes, cucumbers, tuna, and broccoli cole slaw mix are tossed in a dressing with mayonnaise and Italian-style salad dressing.
title: Pittsburgh Football Sunday Pasta Salad

description: This side dish is almost like a dessert. Sweet Italian sausage is baked with egg noodles and apples with a cinnamon-sugar topping.
title: Sausage, Apples, and Noodles

description: This is a very old Pennsylvania Dutch treat, a sort of milk and sugar pie made usually for children, as a way to use up leftover pie dough. This makes an odd-looking pie, but it tastes better than it looks.  I have heard this called many names, among them Slap Jack, Flippy, Shlop Boi, Flitche, Flabby, or even Stingy Pie!
title: Milk Flitcher Pie

description: This very sweet and creamy pie is made of two layers. The first is whipped up with molasses, sugar, water, lemon juice and rind, and a bit of flour. The second is a creamy, sweet buttermilk topping. They both go into a pie shell that is baked, cooled and served to raves.
title: Montgomery Pie

description: It's gooey sweet and unadorned by a top crust. What better invitation to come join the party does a hungry insect need? It should be called "molasses pie," but it's whimsically named shoofly because its "open" structure lures flies that must be shooed away. Shoofly Pie is thought to be a Pennsylvania Dutch creation, and may be a direct descendant of "Centennial Cake" introduced at the first World's Fair -- the 1876 Philadelphia Centennial Exposition.
title: Traditional Shoofly Pie

description: Pork is roasted with garlic and herbs, then topped with savory cooked spinach and manchego or provolone cheese and piled into crusty sandwich rolls in this South Philly favorite.
title: Philadelphia Style Roast Pork Sandwiches

description: Boilo is the high-octane mulled alcoholic drink that has been served hot in the coal regions of Pennsylvania for over a hundred years. It will warm you up and cure what ails you.
title: Coal Region Boilo

description: This recipe combines Mexican food with a Philly-style filling to deliver a crispy tortilla wrapped around beef, bell pepper, onion, and cheese.
title: Cheesesteak Chimichanga

description: This simple pie's molasses filling is stirred up, combined with a brown sugar crumble, and poured into a prepared crust. Then a bit more crumble is sprinkled on the top. Serve it with whipped cream or ice cream.
title: Shoofly Pie III

description: A quick and easy variation on the classic Shoofly Pie.
title: Shoofly Pie IV

description: A rich pound cake made with confectioners' sugar. Tastes best without frosting!
title: Pennsylvania Dutch Pound Cake

description: This pie whips up in a wink, but it tastes like you 've been in the kitchen for hours. A brown sugar crumble is stirred into the molasses and egg filling, and then it 's sprinkled on top of the pie before it 's baked. The result is a gooey, not-to-sweet, delicious pie that begs to be topped with scoops of vanilla ice cream.
title: Shoofly Pie I

description: Anyone who has been to Pittsburgh can tell you about the wonderful Primanti Brothers sandwiches which are a local delicacy. Coleslaw, fries, cheese, and meat (or no meat for you veggies) on thickly sliced Italian bread brings a taste of Pittsburgh to wherever you may be. You can substitute your favorite meat for the capicola.
title: Primanti-Style Sandwiches

description: This is made in early spring, usually Easter, when the new dandelions are sweet and crisp. It is from my grandma, Callie Brosius, who was Pennsylvania Dutch and a great cook. This is usually served with boiled potatoes with ham at Easter.
title: Dandelion Dressing

description: Famous Pittsburgh-style chipped ham sandwiches are flavored with bacon, sweet pickles, and barbecue sauce, and baked until hot. Beloved throughout Pennsylvania and parts of West Virginia, they're perfect for watching football.
title: Uncle Bo's Hot Sandwiches

description: This dish is a holiday tradition in our family that dates back several generations.  I think it's origins are from the Pennsylvania Dutch country.  It is quick, easy and a definite compliment to the holiday table.
title: Grandma's Cracker Dressing

description: Christmas cookies are dipped in white candy coating and sprinkled with coconut and optional colorful sprinkles. They'll shine on your cookie tray. Vary the flavor by adding mint extract or other favorite flavors.
title: Pennsylvania Snow Drops

description: Sweet and spicy deep-fried hot wings, doused in a buttery sauce enriched with habanero pepper, honey, and bourbon, are a classic snack for cheering on your favorite team.
title: Lubed-Up Hot Wings

description: Chicken noodle soup made with thick kluski noodles and white corn is a traditional comfort food from south central Pennsylvania. This version has short cuts that will get bowls of hearty soup on the table in under an hour.
title: Short-Cut PA Dutch Chicken Corn Soup

description: An apple and molasses brine gives a slow-cooked pork roast deep flavors. The roast simmers for hours with apples, carrots, cranberries, walnuts, and seasonings.
title: Brined Pork and Sauerkraut

description: This recipe blends a Philadelphia-style cheesesteak with chili for a unique crowd-pleaser sure to get your football party guests talking between bites.
title: 'Whiz Wit' Chili

description: Crispy potato chips add a crunchy crust to these zesty tuna melts with pickles and red onion, perfect for a creamy, cheesy dinner for two.
title: Mary Pat's Tuna Melt

description: A corn syrup and molasses filling is poured into an unbaked pie crust, topped with a brown sugar and shortening crumble, and baked. This Pennsylvania Dutch recipe makes a mighty find sweet and gooey pie.
title: Not-Too- Dry Shoofly Pie

description: Soft at first, these cookies harden into 'dunkers' after about 3 weeks. (Yes, they keep a long time!)  They need a mold for the traditional Pennsylvania Dutch cookie, but I bet that they can be made by simply cutting them out. You can substitute other flavorings for anise - lemon and almond are good.
title: Springerle VI

description: This is a Pennsylvania Dutch recipe for Lebkuchen.
title: Lebkuchen (Lep Kuchen)

description: A salad of romaine lettuce, cucumber, and hard-cooked egg slices serves as a bed for French fries and steak in this unique salad recipe.
title: Steak 'n' Fries Salad

description: Pork is topped with sauerkraut, apple, and onion and roasted for several hours in this hearty dish traditionally served on New Year's.
title: Pork and Sauerkraut

description: A big pot full of hearty black-eyed peas flavored with smoky garlic kielbasa (or 'kielbasy') and smoked turkey wings, plus a gallon or more of turkey stock, will bring you, your friends, and all your neighbors good luck for the new year. Serve with hard cider.
title: Toddly Man's Big House Black-Eyed Peas

description: This is an old-fashioned, but easy-to-make devil's food cake recipe.  Pound cake like texture and sinfully chocolately.  This is from an old Philadelphia Bakery. Great when frosted with Chocolate Fudge Buttercream Frosting.
title: Devil's Food Cake I

description: A pizza with the filling in the middle! Pizza dough is slathered with sauce, then stuffed with ham, sausage, salami, pepperoni, mozzarella cheese, and a few vegetables.
title: Stromboli

description: All of the flavors of a Philly cheese steak in a creamy dip.
title: Tammy's Philly Cheese Steak Dip

description: This is a very rich, sweet, gooey, buttery cake. I store leftovers in the refrigerator and they taste just like cheesecake! Yummy!
title: Philadelphia Style Butter Cake

description: This is a quick, great tasting sandwich that's a little spicy. This spice mixture is similar to the (great) Philly Steak Sandwich recipe submitted by Wendy L, but modified for the Southwestern flavor. The sauce is best prepared before hand to let flavors blend.
title: Southwestern Chicken Pitas with Chipotle Sauce

description: Make this anise-flavored eggy Easter bread in the traditional style of Italian bakeries in south Philadelphia. Formed into a twist, and sprinkled with colored nonpareils, it will be a new favorite.
title: Italian Easter Bread (Anise Flavored)

description: All you need is milk, cream, sugar, and pure vanilla extract to make a batch of smooth, perfect vanilla ice cream.
title: How to Make Vanilla Ice Cream

description: Hamburgers made with sauteed onions, green peppers and mushrooms, topped with mozzarella cheese and Italian-style dressing.
title: Eddie's Special Burgers

description: An Asian-inspired version of a Philly cheese steak--thinly sliced steak is cooked with onion, cheese spread, and a splash of teriyaki sauce, and served on sandwich rolls.
title: Philly Cheese Steak

description: Jumbo soft pretzels, topped with hot crab and cheese, are an East Coast favorite and a crab-lover's dream.
title: Crab and Jack Pretzel

description: Philly cheesesteak meets quesadillas when steak, bell peppers, onions, and Cheddar cheese are baked between tortillas.
title: Philly Cheesesteak Quesadillas

description: This recipe yields a big baking dish filled with a hearty macaroni and cheese dish jazzed up with garlic and chicken.
title: Garlic Chicken Mac and Cheese

description: Chef John's recipe for mini Philly cheesesteaks will be the hit of your next football party!
title: Mini Philly Cheesesteaks

description: This is my husband's secret recipe from Austin Texas. We always serve this to our favorite friends. A very straightforward margarita with no added sugar.

description: This slow-cooked chili is great for parties or cold winter nights.

description: This ground turkey and butternut squash casserole is a quick meal to prepare on busy weeknights.

description: This is a wonderful dish for cold winter days that really fills you up! My mother used to make this for my family and it quickly became a favorite. This isn't your normal 'hot' chili and it's a great change of pace. It's best when served with buttered saltine crackers. This chili also freezes well.

description: This dish is colorful and the ingredients prepared ahead of time. Your family and friends will love this recipe!   Note: the most time consuming part of this recipe is making the paste for the sauce (it gives an unique flavor and is worth the effort). The paste can be made ahead of time and stored in the fridge. Bring to room temperature before adding to the sauce.   Serve with your favorite noodles (1b of dry) or with mashed potatoes (5 medium.)

description: This is a really easy BBQ brisket recipe that I got from Texas.  There are only 3 ingredients besides the brisket, and it turns out really tender.  Better with a brisket that is not too closely trimmed.

description: Cold black tea with the refreshing tang of orange and lemon juices, a li'l sugah and the perfect garnish of sliced lemon and lime.

description: Sprinkle crushed tortilla chips over spicy eggs and wrap in a tortilla with Cheddar cheese for a Tex-Mex breakfast favorite from central Texas.

I have had it before with carrots, which I do enjoy, but I prefer it best when it is very simple. This is a very inexpensive dish.

It is a recipe that's been in our family for years, but I want to share it so everybody can enjoy it for the Holidays!!!  You will never want to use any other pumpkin pie recipe from now on. A wonderful option is to sprinkle the finished pie with almond toffee brickle chips.
